# Markdown Rules for NAS Infrastructure Project

## Formatting Standards
- Use ATX-style headers (`# ## ###`)
- Maximum line length: 120 characters
- Use consistent list markers (`-` for unordered, `1.` for ordered)
- Include trailing newline at end of files

## Header Structure
- Use ATX-style headers with space after `#`
- Maintain proper hierarchy (no skipped levels)
- Use descriptive header names
- Keep headers concise but informative

## Code Blocks
- Use fenced code blocks with backticks
- Specify language when possible
- Use consistent indentation within code blocks
- Include file paths in code block descriptions

## Links and References
- Use descriptive link text
- Include proper URLs
- Use relative links for internal references
- Validate links regularly

## Lists and Organization
- Use consistent list markers
- Maintain proper indentation
- Use nested lists appropriately
- Keep lists focused and organized

## Documentation Structure
- Include clear file headers
- Use consistent section organization
- Maintain logical flow
- Include usage examples

## Project-Specific Guidelines
- Document role purposes and usage
- Include variable documentation
- Provide setup and configuration instructions
- Include troubleshooting sections

## Code Examples
- Use proper syntax highlighting
- Include complete, working examples
- Document assumptions and prerequisites
- Provide context for complex examples

## Security Documentation
- Document security considerations
- Include access control information
- Document sensitive configuration
- Provide security best practices

## Maintenance
- Keep documentation up to date
- Review and update regularly
- Remove outdated information
- Validate examples periodically

## Common Patterns
```markdown
# Service Name

Brief description of the service and its purpose.

## Configuration

Documentation of configuration options and variables.

### Variables

| Variable | Type | Default | Description |
|----------|------|---------|-------------|
| `var_name` | string | `default_value` | Description |

## Usage

Example usage and common patterns.

## Troubleshooting

Common issues and solutions.
```

## File Organization
- Use descriptive file names
- Group related documentation
- Maintain consistent structure
- Include proper navigation

## Validation
- Use markdownlint for validation
- Check for broken links
- Validate code examples
- Ensure proper formatting

## Pre-commit Integration
- All markdown files are linted with markdownlint
- Use consistent formatting rules
- Check for syntax errors
- Validate link integrity

## Accessibility
- Use descriptive link text
- Include alt text for images
- Maintain proper heading hierarchy
- Use semantic markup

## Version Control
- Include change logs
- Document breaking changes
- Maintain version history
- Track documentation updates
